    "body": "Aqua is a NASA Earth-observation satellite in a sun-synchronous orbit at\napproximately 705 km altitude and 98.2° inclination. It launched from\nVandenberg Air Force Base on 4 May 2002 as the second flagship mission of the\nEarth Observing System (EOS), following Terra. Its original design life was\nsix years; it has now been returning data for over two decades.\n\nAqua carries six instruments — AIRS, AMSU-A, HSB (failed 2003), CERES, MODIS,\nand AMSR-E (retired 2011) — that together measure Earth's water cycle,\ncloud cover, sea-surface temperatures, aerosols, and radiation budget. Its\nMODIS imagery in particular is central to daily global monitoring of\nvegetation, wildfires, and ocean chlorophyll.\n\nAqua flew in the \"A-Train\" formation with several other afternoon sun-sync\nsatellites until a 2022 exit manoeuvre placed it in a lower drift orbit\nahead of end-of-mission. NASA declared the mission ended in its prime\nEarth-science capacity in 2024 and continues to monitor its passive decay\nwhile selected instruments provide reduced data.\n\nAqua's long baseline of cross-calibrated observations has been foundational to\nclimate-trend analyses and weather forecasting worldwide.",
