    "body": "The Chandra X-ray Observatory is one of NASA's four Great Observatories,\nalongside Hubble, Spitzer, and Compton. It launched on STS-93 aboard Space\nShuttle Columbia on 23 July 1999 and was boosted into an unusual highly\nelliptical 64-hour orbit that carries it from ~14,000 km out to ~134,000 km —\nwell above Earth's radiation belts and providing long uninterrupted\nobservations per orbit.\n\nChandra's high-resolution X-ray mirrors (designed by the Smithsonian\nAstrophysical Observatory and built by Hughes Danbury) give it sub-arcsecond\nangular resolution — about 25× sharper than previous X-ray observatories.\nIts instruments, including the Advanced CCD Imaging Spectrometer (ACIS) and\nHigh Resolution Camera (HRC), have produced landmark images of supernova\nremnants, active galactic nuclei, galaxy clusters, and black-hole accretion.\n\nOriginally planned for a five-year mission, Chandra passed its 25th\nanniversary in 2024. Its thermal insulation has degraded over time, limiting\nallowable pointing orientations, but the observatory continues to produce\nscience despite ongoing budget debates within NASA about funding levels.\n\nChandra's key scientific contributions include direct imaging of matter\nfalling into Sgr A* (the Milky Way's central black hole), observations of\nthe Bullet Cluster that helped constrain dark matter models, and ongoing\nmonitoring of supernova remnants and neutron stars.",
