    "body": "GOES-16 (originally GOES-R) is a NOAA geostationary weather satellite, the\nfirst of the GOES-R series. It launched on 19 November 2016 aboard an Atlas V\nfrom Cape Canaveral and operated as \"GOES East\" at 75.2° W longitude from\nDecember 2017, replacing GOES-13. In early 2025 GOES-19 was commissioned\nas the operational GOES East, and GOES-16 was moved to an on-orbit standby\nposition.\n\nAt geostationary altitude (~35,786 km over the equator), GOES-16 keeps pace\nwith Earth's rotation and stares continuously at the Americas and adjacent\nocean basins. Its Advanced Baseline Imager (ABI) produces full-disk imagery\nevery 10 minutes in 16 spectral bands, and its Geostationary Lightning\nMapper (GLM) provides the first operational continuous lightning detection\nfrom GEO.\n\nGOES-16 data is a backbone of U.S. hurricane, severe-weather, and\naviation-weather forecasting. Its five-minute mesoscale sectors are widely\nused during rapidly developing convective events, and its space-environment\ninstruments feed NOAA's Space Weather Prediction Center.\n\nDesigned for ~15 years of service, GOES-16 is expected to remain an active\non-orbit spare through the end of the decade.",
