    "body": "GPS IIF-9 (Navstar 72, USA-258) is a U.S. Air Force (now Space Force) GPS\nBlock IIF navigation satellite launched on 2 August 2014 aboard an Atlas V\nfrom Cape Canaveral. It operates in a medium Earth orbit at roughly 20,200 km\naltitude with a 55° inclination in one of six orbital planes — the standard\nGPS constellation geometry that guarantees global four-satellite coverage.\n\nBlock IIF satellites were the twelfth generation of GPS spacecraft. They\nadded a new civil L5 signal (for aviation safety-of-life use), improved\natomic clock accuracy via rubidium standards, and offered a longer 12-year\ndesign life than earlier blocks. Twelve IIF vehicles were launched between\n2010 and 2016.\n\nLike every GPS satellite, GPS IIF-9 continuously broadcasts precise timing\nand ephemeris data. Receivers on the ground combine signals from four or\nmore visible satellites to compute position, velocity, and time — the\nfoundation of almost all modern civilian positioning, navigation, and\ntiming infrastructure. The GPS constellation is complemented by other\nGNSS systems: Europe's Galileo, Russia's GLONASS, and China's BeiDou.\n\nGPS IIF-9 remains operational as of 2025, alongside the growing GPS III\nseries (launched from 2018 onward) that are gradually replacing the older\nBlock IIR and IIF vehicles.",
