    "body": "Hitomi (originally ASTRO-H) was a Japanese X-ray astronomy satellite built by\nJAXA with contributions from NASA, ESA, CSA, and several universities. It\nlaunched on 17 February 2016 on an H-IIA rocket from Tanegashima and was\nrenamed Hitomi (\"pupil of the eye\") after reaching orbit.\n\nHitomi carried four co-aligned instruments, including the groundbreaking Soft\nX-ray Spectrometer (SXS) — a cryogenically cooled microcalorimeter array\ncapable of spectral resolution previously unachievable in the X-ray band.\nDuring its brief commissioning, SXS delivered a landmark measurement of gas\nmotions in the Perseus galaxy cluster, demonstrating the potential of\ncalorimeter spectroscopy.\n\nOn 26 March 2016, a chain of attitude-control failures caused Hitomi to\nenter an uncontrolled spin and break apart. JAXA declared the mission lost\non 28 April 2016 after ~38 days in orbit. The debris remained catalogued\nunder NORAD 41337 as it slowly re-entered over subsequent years.\n\nHitomi's scientific legacy lives on through the follow-on mission XRISM\n(X-Ray Imaging and Spectroscopy Mission), launched September 2023, which\nre-flew a calorimeter-based instrument derived from Hitomi's SXS design.",
