    "body": "The Hubble Space Telescope is a 2.4-metre optical/UV/NIR observatory jointly\noperated by NASA and ESA. It launched on STS-31 aboard Space Shuttle Discovery\non 24 April 1990 and orbits at roughly 540 km altitude with a 28.5° inclination.\n\nHubble's early spherical aberration was corrected by astronauts during Servicing\nMission 1 (STS-61, December 1993), and four subsequent shuttle servicing\nmissions upgraded instruments and reaction wheels, most recently SM4 in May\n2009. No further crewed servicing is possible now that the Shuttle is retired.\n\nHubble has produced some of the most scientifically and culturally important\nastronomical images of the modern era — the Deep Fields, the Pillars of\nCreation, and direct observations of exoplanet atmospheres among them. Its\nobservations have been cited in tens of thousands of peer-reviewed papers.\n\nThe telescope continues to operate in a degraded-but-functional mode as of\n2025. Its orbit is slowly decaying; without a reboost it is expected to\nre-enter the atmosphere some time in the mid-to-late 2030s. NASA and private\npartners have studied reboost missions but none is currently funded.",
