    "body": "The International Space Station (ISS) is a large modular space station in low\nEarth orbit, operated since 1998 by a partnership between NASA, Roscosmos,\nESA, JAXA, and CSA. The first module, Zarya, launched on 20 November 1998;\nthe station has been continuously crewed since Expedition 1 arrived on\n2 November 2000.\n\nIt orbits at roughly 400 km mean altitude with an inclination of ~51.6°,\ncompleting one lap every ~92 minutes and crossing most of the inhabited world\nbetween latitudes ±51.6°. Crews of typically six to seven astronauts rotate\nthrough six-month increments, conducting research in microgravity across\nbiology, materials science, fundamental physics, and Earth observation.\n\nPropulsive reboosts — from visiting Progress, Cygnus, or Zvezda itself —\ncounter atmospheric drag and keep the station from decaying. Current NASA/ISS\npartner plans have ISS operating through at least 2030, with a planned\ncontrolled deorbit thereafter using a dedicated deorbit vehicle under\ndevelopment by SpaceX.\n\nAs of 2025, the ISS remains the largest crewed object in orbit, massing over\n420 tonnes with a habitable volume roughly equivalent to a Boeing 747 interior.",
