    "body": "The James Webb Space Telescope (JWST) is a 6.5-metre segmented infrared\nobservatory operated by NASA in partnership with ESA and CSA. It launched on\nan Ariane 5 from Kourou on 25 December 2021 and completed a month-long\ncruise, sunshield deployment, and mirror unfurl before arriving at the\nSun–Earth L2 Lagrange point in January 2022.\n\nWebb does not orbit Earth: it orbits L2 in a halo orbit roughly 1.5 million km\nsunward-facing-away from Earth. That means its NORAD catalog entry (50463)\nexists but is not useful for live SGP4 propagation — standard tracking tools\ncannot compute a meaningful altitude or ground track for it. The mission\ncarries enough propellant for science operations well past 2040 thanks to an\nunusually efficient launch insertion.\n\nJWST's four instruments (NIRCam, NIRSpec, MIRI, NIRISS/FGS) probe the earliest\ngalaxies in the universe, the atmospheres of exoplanets, star-forming regions,\nand objects in our own solar system. By 2025 it had already reshaped\nunderstanding of early-universe galaxy formation and provided the first direct\nmid-infrared detections of CO₂ in exoplanet atmospheres.\n\nBecause it lives at L2, JWST observes nearly the full sky over the course of\na year but cannot be serviced by humans — it is too far away.",
