    "body": "Tiangong (\"Heavenly Palace\") is China's third-generation crewed space station,\noperated by the China Manned Space Agency (CMSA). The core module Tianhe\nlaunched on 29 April 2021 on a Long March 5B from Wenchang; NORAD catalog\nnumber 48274 tracks this core module, which anchors the rest of the station.\n\nTwo laboratory modules — Wentian (July 2022) and Mengtian (October 2022) —\njoined Tianhe to complete the baseline T-shaped configuration. Tiangong\norbits at roughly 380–450 km altitude and 41.5° inclination, substantially\nlower in latitude than the ISS. The station is normally occupied by\nthree-person Shenzhou crews rotating on roughly six-month increments.\n\nTiangong supports microgravity science across biology, fluid physics, fundamental\nphysics, and life-support research, plus Earth observation using a deployable\nco-orbiting telescope module (Xuntian) scheduled to join later in the\ndecade. A fourth module expansion to a cross-shape is planned.\n\nChina has opened Tiangong to limited international collaboration through UN\nOffice for Outer Space Affairs partnerships, and has signalled that\nTiangong may be the only crewed orbital outpost after ISS retires.",
